The paper deals with the NP-completeness of planar variants of the monotone satisfiability problem, which is a classic problem in computational complexity theory. The paper uses techniques from graph theory and computational geometry to analyze the problem, which suggests that it may be relevant to several subfields of computer science. Specifically, cs.CC (Computational Complexity), cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), and cs.CG (Computational Geometry) are likely sub-categories given the focus on complexity analysis and graph drawing algorithms. Additionally, cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) and cs.LG (Machine Learning) may also be relevant given the use of combinatorial techniques and the potential applications of the problem to decision-making and optimization problems.
